sentence: The Dow Jones Industrial Average rose to its fifth record high in six sessions and its 25th so far this year as Wall Street continued to grind higher on the heels of retail giant Wal-Mart ( WMT ) posting better-than-expected Q3 results and Warren Buffett stepping up to buy Duracell batteries from Proctor & Gamble ( PG ).
The S&P 500 and the Nasdaq Composite Index eked out small gains as well.
Technology and consumer stocks were the lone sectors in the S&P 500 today to finish higher, although that was enough to lift the major market indices to narrow gains.
Energy stocks again proved to be the largest drag on upward momentum for equities, with crude oil futures today falling under $75 per barrel for its lowest price in four years.
Wal-Mart ( WMT ) helped both the Dow and consumer stocks to higher closes after beating Wall Street expectations with its Q3 results.
Consumer staple companies also got a lift from Berkshire Hathaway as it agreed to a $4.7 billion deal for P&G's Duracell unit.

Economic data had little impact on market direction Thursday with the Labor Department reporting initial jobless claims rose by a greater-than-expected 12,000 to 290,000 first-time claims for unemployment benefits.
Crude oil for December delivery settled $2.97 lower at $74.21 per barrel while December natural gas dropped 21 cents to $3.98 per 1 million BTU.
But December gold rose Thursday, climbing $2.40 to $1,161.50 per ounce.

Here's where the U.S. markets stood at the end-of-day:

(+) ZAZA, Earns $0.83 per share during its Q3, reversing a $2.01 per share net loss during the same quarter last year.
Revenue jumps 144% year over year to $2.7 mln.
No analyst estimates were available for comparison.
(+) CYBR, Q3 EPS of $0.12 crushes projections by $0.11 per share.
Revenue grows 65.5% to $27.96 mln, topping Street consensus by $7.07 mln.
Projected Q4 earnings beat estimates by at least $0.02 per share; revenue outlook also exceeds expectations.
(+) FUEL, Adjusted Q3 net loss of $6.6 million, or a $0.18 per share, beats consensus view by $0.12 per share.
Revenue grew 63% to $102.1 million, topping estimates by $3.43 mln.
Sees Q4 revenue exceeding Street view by as much as $25 mln.
(-) LOCM, Revenue declines 22.7% year over year to $18.1 mln, upstaging the local search and advertising firm narrowing GAAP net loss compared with year-ago levels to $0.06 per share.
No analyst estimates were available for comparison.
(-) URRE, Completes non-cash asset exchange with Rio Grande Resources Corp and Uranco Inc.
